  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration. Here are legal definitions and key elements based on prominent legal frameworks:\n\n### 1. **United States**\nUnder U.S. law, money laundering is defined in the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957)**:\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits conducting financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activity with the intent to:\n     - Promote illegal activity.\n     - Conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds.\n     - Evade taxes or reporting requirements.\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits engaging in monetary transactions involving criminally derived property exceeding $10,000.\n\n### 2. **United Kingdom**\nIn the UK, money laundering is defined under the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)**:\n   - It criminalizes actions involving criminal property, defined as property obtained through unlawful conduct.\n   - Key offenses include:\n     - Concealing, disguising, converting, transferring, or removing criminal property.\n     - Entering into or becoming involved in an arrangement related to criminal property.\n     - Acquiring, using, or possessing criminal property.\n\n### 3. **European Union**\nThe EU defines money laundering in the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**, most recently the **Sixth AMLD (Directive (EU) 2018/1673)**:\n   - It criminalizes the following when committed intentionally:\n     - Converting or transferring property to conceal its illicit origin.\n     - Concealing or disguising the nature, source, location, disposition, movement, or ownership of property.\n     - Acquiring, possessing, or using property derived from criminal activity.\n   - It also includes aiding, abetting, and attempting these acts.\n\n### 4. **International Framework**\nThe **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** provides global standards for combating money laundering:\n   - Money laundering is defined as the processing of criminal proceeds to disguise their illegal origin.\n   - FATF\u2019s **40 Recommendations** outline measures for countries to implement to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### Common Elements Across Jurisdictions:\n   - **Illegal Proceeds**: Funds obtained through criminal activity (e.g., drug trafficking, fraud, corruption).\n   - **Intent to Conceal**: Actions taken to disguise the origin, ownership, or control of the funds.\n   - **Financial Transactions**: Involvement in transactions or arrangements to legitimize the funds.\n\nPenalties for money laundering vary by jurisdiction but often include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Enforcement is carried out by agencies such as the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) in the U.S., the National Crime Agency (NCA) in the UK, and Europol in the EU.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
